content.focus_group: K-5 students who receive Multilingual Learner services. Instructional practices to support growth for all students.
content.strategies_summarized: To achieve 70% of multilingual learners in grades 2-5 scoring in the Low or Minimal Risk range on the Spring 2028 FastBridge aReading Assessment, Alcott Elementary will implement a comprehensive, multi-faceted approach combining evidence-based literacy curricula, technology tools, collaborative structures, and instructional practices. The school will establish strong foundational skills in K-2 through consistent use of the Heggerty Phonemic Awareness and UFLI curricula, while supporting differentiation across K-5 with Lexia and optional Word Study resources, all monitored through yearly use reviews. Additionally, staff will implement tiered MTSS interventions, utilize frequent small-group instruction with flexible grouping, and engage students through discussion, reflection, and peer collaboration aligned with Danielson's Framework for Teaching, supported by ongoing professional learning communities that use data protocols and the Critical Data Matrix to monitor progress. Regular collaboration meetings between classroom and ML services staff, yearly WIDA Screener reviews, scheduled intervention blocks, and exploration of Seesaw as a differentiated learning tool will ensure that instructional decisions are data-informed and responsive to student needs.

content.strategies_summarized: To achieve 85% favorable responses in Social Awareness on the 2028 Spring Panorama survey, Alcott Elementary will implement a comprehensive, school-wide approach centered on the "Alcott CAREs" PBIS program and evidence-based SEL curricula including Zones of Regulation and Purposeful People's "Be Kind" program. Counselors will deliver tailored classroom lessons on social awareness strategies and Zones of Regulation with empathy components, with understanding and application assessed through student checks, while all staff will consistently praise positive social awareness behaviors as measured through "Orca Tails" counts. Additionally, the school will establish regular classroom and program meeting check-ins to reinforce SEL skills, provide students access to calming zones in learning spaces, celebrate student and family differences through Recognition Weeks and Heritage Months, and ensure ongoing staff training on equity and inclusion throughout the year, with implementation monitored through staff reviews, confirmations, and attendance records.

content.strategies_summarized: Audubon Elementary will establish a building schedule prioritizing protected core literacy instruction, small group classroom learning, and an intervention block for all students, while implementing UFLI across primary classrooms supplemented by Heggerty and Wonders to ensure robust instruction and tiered supports for all learners. The school will strengthen staff collaboration among general education, special education, multilingual, and reading specialist staff through structured PLC time and joint planning, supported by ongoing professional development in the Science of Reading, UFLI implementation, and SIOP strategies. Additionally, staff will intentionally preteach, teach, and review literacy and mathematical content language in small and large groups, maximize collaboration to align multilingual practices with content instruction, and modify assignments as needed to remove language barriers, with progress monitored through visible schedules, professional development records, and team planning documentation.

content.focus_group: Multilingual Students, especially those who are in 3rd, 4th, and 5th grade and who are receiving supports from the ML program.
content.strategies_summarized: Audubon Elementary will close the math achievement gap for multilingual learners by implementing a protected math schedule that enables small group instruction and targeted interventions, while carefully selecting individualized ML services such as push-in and pull-out support that align with special education and reading instruction. Staff will collaborate across grade levels and departments to integrate ML practices with math content instruction, provide professional development in SIOP strategies, and intentionally preteach and review mathematical vocabulary using varied instructional approaches. Additionally, the school will modify assignments as needed to remove language barriers and identify potential linguistic obstacles that may impede student understanding of mathematical concepts.
content.currentdata: The student population at Audubon shows that at least 50% of students are multi-lingual learners and have varying needs related to academic language development: 25% of students are multi-lingual and are actively receiving ML services. 25% previously received ML services and have exited the program. 50% have never qualified for ML services, but may speak multiple languages. Smarter Balanced Assessment scores from the 2024-2025 school year show the following percentages of students meeting standard in math: 59% of students eligible for ML services 90% of students previously eligible for ML services 85% of students never eligible for ML services This data along with teacher observation indicates a need for robust supports to help students develop academic language that will reduce the language barrier in math.

content.strategies_summarized: To help all students feel connected to the school, adults, and other students, Audubon Elementary will implement multiple strategies including assessing student sense of belonging through tools like Panorama surveys and staff-created assessments, increasing social opportunities through mixed-grade recess groups and flexible lunch seating arrangements, conducting counselor-led small group lessons that include students across various programs, and facilitating regular community circles in classrooms using prompt cards and other resources. These coordinated efforts will be monitored through classroom lesson plans, lunchroom practices, and counselor planning notes to ensure that students develop meaningful connections within the school community.
content.currentdata: As a school we have focused on student sense of belonging for many School Improvement Plans, and both Panorama and building created measures continue to show a percentage of students who feel connected at 65-75%. The percentage has not shown a significant change since 2019. In previous years we have focused on schoolwide practices, teacher student relationships through classroom SEL supports, and student to student connections. This year we continue to look for ways to connect each and every student to the school community. This year we will recenter practices and collaborate more efficiently to increase student sense of belonging. We will reimagine SEL lessons with special education staff and the counselor collaborating closely with teachers for co-teaching, whole group, and small group lessons as needed.

content.focus_area: Solving problems involving the four operations and patterns.
content.strategies_summarized: A. G. Bell Elementary will implement targeted small group instruction focused on math patterns and operations, utilizing screening tools such as FastBridge and Dreambox to identify students by need and ability while dedicating 30-50 minutes daily in the master schedule for differentiated instruction and Illustrative Math Centers. Teachers will engage students through gamification strategies (Kahoot, Bingo, card games) and consistent Dreambox usage during small group rotations, supported by professional learning on structuring math small groups and using curriculum resources effectively. Additionally, the school will enhance student engagement and expression through Instructional Playbook and SIOP strategies that increase student talk and participation opportunities, implement a Student-Generated Street Data Rubric to monitor engagement, and distribute wireless hotspots and devices to extend learning through Dreambox and Xtramath at home, ensuring all K-5 students demonstrate realistic growth on the FastBridge Math assessment.

content.strategies_summarized: A. G. Bell Elementary will implement a comprehensive, multi-faceted approach to build student self-efficacy through integrated curriculum activities, social-emotional learning programs, and school-wide recognition initiatives. The school will embed growth mindset lessons, self-reflection opportunities, and problem-solving activities across academic subjects while simultaneously providing Second Step lessons, monthly attribute focus assemblies emphasizing perseverance, daily self-efficacy-focused morning meetings, student leadership opportunities, and counselor-led small-group instruction for students needing additional support. Additionally, the school will establish robust teacher professional development on collective and student efficacy, implement student-centered goal setting and progress monitoring through data notebooks, and celebrate student achievements through recognition systems, with success measured through completion of building-created surveys, classroom observation data, student participation rates in leadership and affinity groups, and improvements on both the Student Self-Efficacy Survey and Panorama Survey Results.

content.outcome: 88% of students in grades 3 – 5 will be at or above standard in ELA as measured by the Smarter Balanced Assessment in Spring of 2028 Write or revise one or more paragraphs demonstrating ability to stay on topics or use sources; organize ideas and develop supporting evidence/reasons and elaboration.
content.strategies_summarized: To achieve the goal of 88% of students in grades 3-5 reaching or above standard in ELA, Elizabeth Blackwell Elementary School will implement a comprehensive, multi-faceted approach centered on strengthened writing and reading instruction. Teachers across grades K-5 will ensure fidelity in using district-provided writing curriculum while integrating writing instruction across multiple content areas and incorporating culturally responsive teaching strategies that connect to students' backgrounds and interests. Additionally, the school will provide targeted, grade-level instruction—with grades K-2 focusing on topics and supporting details, and grades 3-5 explicitly teaching organizational structure—supported by grade-level teams who will analyze student work against rubrics and annotated samples to adjust instruction, while special education teachers will coordinate schedules to support students during reading intervention blocks. The MTSS team will review FastBridge scores to identify students needing additional support, and teachers will utilize inquiry-based strategies to teach inference skills and leverage SBA Interim Assessments to prepare students for the spring assessments.
content.currentdata: After examining Blackwell’s ELA target data beginning in spring 2022, we have found that performance in some target areas within writing and reading was lower for our students relative to other portions of the test. These target areas were consistent across grades 3, 4, and 5. Specifically, students scored relatively lower in the target area of “writing and revising brief texts.” Included within this target area is writing and revising one or more paragraphs, organizing ideas, and providing supporting evidence and elaboration. The data supports an increased focus on writing and reading instructional strategies at Blackwell. Targeted instruction will be provided across curriculum content areas of writing in mathematics, social studies, and science to lend themselves to naturally harvest writing opportunities for students. During the spring 2025 SBA assessment, relative lower cohort target achievements were noted in the target area of “writing and revising brief texts” and in Reading specifically when “making inferences.” The data supports an increase in focus on these areas in our instruction of these reading and writing areas.

content.focus_area: Math Target Areas: • Grade 3: Represent and solve problems involving multiplication and division. • Grade 4: Use place value understanding and properties of operations to perform multi-digit arithmetic. • Grade 5: Represent and interpret data
content.strategies_summarized: Elizabeth Blackwell Elementary School will implement a comprehensive mathematics improvement plan focused on strengthening instruction and supporting student learning across grades K-5. Teachers will utilize inquiry-based and problem-solving strategies from the adopted curriculum while participating in vertical teaming through LEAP to ensure consistent instruction and student exposure to standards before the Spring 2028 SBA assessment. Additionally, the school will establish regular intervention blocks with specialized schedules for special education students, leverage SBA Interim Assessments and FastBridge data to identify focus areas, assign targeted digital resources like Dreambox and Illustrative Math, and provide instructional coaching support—including dedicated instructional assistants for grades 4-5—to help teachers implement evidence-based strategies such as Building Thinking Classrooms and common problem-solving approaches like the "3 Reads" strategy to support student mastery of multi-step word problems and mathematical discourse.
content.currentdata: After examining Blackwell’s Math target data, we have found grade levels were proficient in mathematics however, there are specific performances in some target areas within mathematics that were lower for our students relative to other portions of the test. The math target areas differed across grades 3, 4, and 5 in the 2023-24 school year were: • Grade 3: Represent and solve problems involving multiplication and division; Solve problems involving the four operations and identify and explain patterns in arithmetic; Represent and interpret data. • Grade 4: Use the four operations with whole numbers to solve problems; Generalize place value understanding for multi-digit whole numbers; Use place value understanding and properties of operations to perform multi-digit arithmetic; Solve problems involving measurement and conversion of measurements from a larger unit to a smaller unit; Draw and identify lines and angles and classify shapes by properties of their lines and angles. • Grade 5: Graph points on the coordinate plane to solve real-world and mathematical problems. The most recent SBA (spring, 2025) math results demonstrate that these target areas are no longer deemed relatively lower in the students’ proficiency. The math target areas noted on the spring 2025 SBA results showed relatively lower success in two target areas.

content.strategies_summarized: Rachel Carson Elementary will implement a comprehensive, multi-faceted literacy program to improve CBM reading scores from 80% to 100% on track by the end of 2nd grade. The school will employ daily phonemic awareness instruction through Heggerty (P-1 grade band), Wonders Phonemic Awareness (K-2nd, four times weekly), and K-2 UFLI implementation, while simultaneously supporting phonics development through the Wonders Curriculum, Letters and Sounds (preschool through 2nd grade), and increased Lexia usage across the system. content.strategies_summarized: Clara Barton Elementary will implement a comprehensive, multi-tiered approach to increase student belonging through universal social-emotional learning, targeted interventions, and supportive physical spaces. content.strategies_summarized: Discovery Community School will implement a comprehensive, multi-tiered reading intervention approach to achieve this outcome, beginning with whole-class phonemic awareness instruction using Heggerty in grades K-2 with dedicated daily time (10-15 minutes) and collaboration from Safety Net teachers, while simultaneously ensuring explicit phonics instruction is embedded within daily Wonders lessons as observed during administrative monitoring. Additionally, the school will provide targeted Tier 2 small group differentiated instruction for students showing risk indicators in phonemic awareness, phonics, and fluency using Wonders curricular tools and the UFLI curriculum, with progress closely monitored through FastBridge intervention plans and individual student tracking.
content.currentdata: Preventing any student in grades K-2 from demonstrating high risk on the FastBridge End of Year assessments allows for early identification and targeted intervention. This proactive approach helps address reading difficulties before they become more entrenched, reducing long-term learning gaps. Monitoring growth through the Screening to Intervention Report ensures that instruction is responsive and tailored to each student’s needs, promoting equitable learning opportunities. Looking at Fastbridge data, there are 13 students (K- 3rd) demonstrating some to high risk. Early intervention with targeted phonics instruction will help us achieve this goal.

content.currentdata: When students get to middle school, there is a huge shift to reading to learn, versus learning to read. Our current data shows that students grew by a median growth percentile of 53 on the Spring 2025 ELA SBA, 53 on the Spring 2024 ELA SBA and 62 on the Spring 2023 ELA SBA. This means that just about half of our students are growing less than their same age peers with similar score profiles throughout the state. This same data trend is also evident in FastBridge Growth Percentile data from the 2024-2025 school year.

content.strategies_summarized: To achieve 75% of K-5 low-income students scoring "No" or "Low Risk" on FastBridge assessments by Spring 2027, Ella Baker Elementary will implement a comprehensive, data-driven approach across three tiers of instruction. The school will assess all students three times per year using FastBridge progress monitoring, utilize these data through twice-monthly MTSS meetings and collaborative planning between instructional coaches, intervention teams, and classroom teachers to drive small group instruction in both classroom and intervention settings. content.strategies_summarized: Ella Baker Elementary will implement a comprehensive, multi-tiered approach combining universal and targeted strategies to foster both sense of belonging and self-acceptance among K-5 students. At the Tier 1 level, all teachers will explicitly teach the school's motto "Be Kind. Be Brave. Be You. Be the Change" through daily class meetings, intentional classroom and school-wide practices including morning meetings and character circles, and lessons on embracing diversity, while the school will create multiple leadership opportunities and host three schoolwide events annually to build community. For students who indicate lower sense of belonging on the SEL and Panorama surveys (Tier 2), the counselor and CIS will conduct targeted check-ins, implement a "2x10 strategy," facilitate new student support groups, and supervise the Baker Bear Club—an indoor lunch recess program designed to develop social skills in a supportive peer environment. Additionally, the staff will use the National School of Character's 11 Principles as a framework, monitor their own sense of belonging through monthly surveys and connection activities, and utilize targeted Panorama lessons based on assessment data to continuously refine instruction and support.
content.currentdata: In Spring of 2024, 75% of students 3-5th reported a sense of belonging in their Panorama Survey. In Spring of 2024, 51.67% of K-2 students reported that they could be themselves and are respected by others at Ella Baker.
content.engagement_strategies: Students set SECD goals during Family Connection Meetings. Our teachers have developed a set of questions to gather information about their families, the students, and what is important to them. At Partnering with Families, we engage families in community circles and teach them about restorative practices. We host a new family night that focuses on community building, SECD work, restorative practices, and we gather input from families on our partnership. We host 3 listening sessions at Redmond Ridge Apartments to gather input and partner with families.

content.outcome: By spring 2026, student Panorama scores will increase by 5% in the category of Emotional Regulation.
content.strategies_summarized: To achieve a 5% increase in student Panorama scores for Emotional Regulation by spring 2026, Explorer Community School will implement a comprehensive, multi-tiered approach centered on daily regulation practices and social-emotional learning. Teachers will conduct daily check-ins using Zones of Regulation during classroom instruction and lead mindfulness/regulation strategies during morning meetings, while the school will reinforce common social-emotional language through monthly SOAR (PBIS) expectation videos and weekly Monday morning announcements featuring scripts from Character Strong/Purposeful People. Additionally, the school will establish and promote calming spaces throughout the building—including calm-down kits in classrooms, at recess, and in the lunch area—and will create a dedicated Motor Room with trained staff to support students' sensory and emotional regulation needs, with implementation measured through "Tell Me Tuesday" surveys (grades 2-5), teacher monthly check-ins, student feedback via Seesaw, and Motor Room usage tracking.

content.focus_area: Sense of Belonging and Emotional Regulation
content.strategies_summarized: Robert Frost Elementary School will implement a comprehensive approach to support emotional regulation and create a safe, inclusive learning environment for all students, particularly female and Hispanic/Latinx female students. The school will provide staff professional learning on trauma-sensitive practices and brain research with Dr. Shotland, implement the Purposeful People and Second Step curriculum during designated SEL time, and train recess and lunchroom supervisors in de-escalation and emotional regulation strategies, with progress monitored through decreased office and recess referrals and administrative walkthroughs. Additionally, the school counselor will provide small-group interventions using the Second Step Curriculum for students needing targeted support, and a 4th and 5th Grade Student Council will be established to amplify student voice and ensure their needs are heard through regular listening sessions.
content.currentdata: The results of the Panorama Student Survey Data (Spring 2025) identified that: • Frost students responded with a higher percentage (92%) of positive responses in Supportive Relationships than the district average and up 3% from 2024. • Frost students scored 7 percentage points lower than the average for the Lake Washington School District on Challenging Feelings, such as worry, anger, and sadness. This was also a comparatively higher impact area for students identifying as female and greater impact for students identifying as Hispanic/Latinx Female.

content.outcome: By Spring 2026, 80% of K-5 students will score at or above standard as measured by FastBridge (Grades K-2) and the ELA Smarter Balanced Assessment (Grades 3-5).
content.strategies_summarized: To achieve this outcome, Juanita Elementary School will implement a comprehensive literacy approach across grades K-5 by having teachers collaborate horizontally and vertically to teach literacy standards with fidelity using Wonders, UFLI, and Heggerty curricula, while integrating strategies from the LWSD Instructional Playbook and research-based literacy technology through Lexia. Teachers and interventionists will analyze assessment data from multiple sources to inform flexible grouping and differentiated instruction aligned with Universal Design for Learning principles, adjusting instruction based on student performance and instructional needs. All grade-level teams will regularly review assessment data to monitor progress and make real-time instructional adjustments necessary to move students toward the 80% proficiency goal.

content.focus_area: Number Sense, Computation and Fluency (Claim 1 – Concepts and Procedures SBA)
content.strategies_summarized: To achieve 80% of K-5th grade students scoring at or above standard by Spring 2026, Juanita Elementary School will implement a comprehensive mathematics improvement plan centered on small group instruction and differentiated learning. Teachers will participate in professional development focused on small group math instruction and inquiry-based learning through Building Thinking Classrooms, while designing lessons using UDL principles and the LWSD Instructional Playbook to support flexible grouping and differentiated instruction. Additionally, students will engage with research-based technology through DreamBox, participate in skip counting activities to build number sense and multiplication proficiency, and teachers will regularly use data from IM Unit Assessments and Cool Down Sections to monitor student progress and adjust instruction accordingly.
content.currentdata: Data analysis of our SBA scores from prior years indicates that the area needing the most attention is the Concepts & Procedures claim, specifically in the area of multiplication.
content.engagement_strategies: Teachers will engage students and their families in collaborative setting and monitoring mathematics goals through respectful, culturally responsive practices that honor the diverse strengths of our school community. Our goal is to build meaningful, two-way partnerships that empower families to support math learning at home in ways that feel natural, inclusive, and connected to daily life. To strengthen these partnerships, we will: • Provide math fluency resources, including at-home games, weekly fluency logs, and access to IM (Illustrative Mathematics) family letters to help families understand unit goals and vocabulary. • Share pictures and examples of “math in action” from classrooms and school events to illustrate what high-quality math learning looks like. • Collaborate with families to build math automaticity, offering simple practice routines and strategies that can be incorporated into home life. • Send home IM Unit Family Information and website links that support grade-level math concepts. • Invite families to share photos of math in their real lives, such as cooking, budgeting, gardening, or building—celebrating the many cultural and everyday ways math shows up at home. • Promote accessible family math games such as Yahtzee, cribbage, and other culturally relevant games that support counting, patterning, probability, and strategic thinking. • Host class visits with math experts in the community—such as bakers, carpenters, engineers, gamers, or artists—to show real- world applications of mathematical thinking. • Encourage families to use math in daily routines, such as cooking measurements, time management, comparing prices, or planning schedules, reinforcing math as a practical life skill. Through these collaborative strategies, we aim to create a math learning community where students see themselves as capable mathematicians and families feel confident, supported, and valued as partners in their child’s mathematical growth.

content.outcome: Equity
content.focus_group: Disproportionality of students who are black qualifying for Special Education in the areas of social, emotional, and behavior.
content.strategies_summarized: To achieve equity, Juanita Elementary School will implement a comprehensive, school-wide approach centered on social-emotional learning, cultural responsiveness, and relationship-building. All staff will engage in trauma-informed practices and explicit instruction in self-regulation strategies (including Jaguar PRIDE, Zones of Regulation, and PurposeFull People), while simultaneously implementing Culturally Responsive Teaching practices that move beyond surface-level culture. Additionally, the school will intentionally foster peer relationships and teach respectful interactions through structured play in K-2 classrooms and partner work in grades 3-5, while facilitating daily self-regulating activities and frequent classroom meetings focused on student resiliency and problem-solving. Success will be measured through increases in staff implementation of these practices, student reports of positive peer connections, teacher consistency in teaching respectful interactions, daily engagement in grounding strategies, and the percentage of class meetings dedicated to building student resiliency.
content.currentdata: OSPI Disproportionality Data & Panorama Data
content.engagement_strategies: Staff will actively engage families in Social-Emotional Learning by providing accessible, culturally responsive, and meaningful opportunities for collaboration. Our goal is to strengthen the home–school connection and empower families to reinforce SEL skills in ways that reflect their values, traditions, and lived experiences. To deepen SEL partnerships with families, we will: • Host SEL-focused learning opportunities during Open House, curriculum nights, and PTA meetings to build shared understanding of core SEL skills and practices. • Share family-friendly strategies and resources through newsletters, videos, and classroom updates to support SEL development at home. • Invite families to share what respect looks like in their family, helping students recognize diverse cultural expressions of kindness, responsibility, and care. • Encourage families to use movies, videos, and short stories that promote positive SEL messages, providing examples and recommendations to help spark meaningful conversations at home. • Offer opportunities for families to share how they celebrate important traditions, supporting cultural awareness, belonging, and identity development across the school community. • Provide platforms for families to share about their careers and areas of expertise, highlighting SEL skills such as teamwork, collaboration, resilience, and problem-solving in real-life contexts. Through these ongoing efforts, we aim to create a school culture where students feel understood, supported, and connected, and where families are valued as essential partners in nurturing social-emotional development.

content.strategies_summarized: Helen Keller Elementary will implement a comprehensive, grade-level approach to reading instruction and family engagement to achieve 80% student growth on Fastbridge assessments. Across kindergarten through second grade, teachers will utilize UFLI and Heggerty phonics programs alongside family engagement strategies such as co-creating reading goals at conferences and using platforms like SeeSaw, while upper elementary grades will focus on fluency tracking, intervention and enrichment groups, and weekly family communications. Additionally, administrators will provide observational feedback on reading interventions, engage in PLCs to review growth data, and actively connect with families of students not on track, while special education teachers will collaborate using UFLI as an intervention and support executive functioning skills to ensure all students make progress toward low-risk status.

content.outcome: By June 2026, 80% of Black/Black-Hispanic/Black two or more races students at Keller will demonstrate growth in social-emotional competencies related to belonging, self-efficacy, and school connectedness, as measured by SEL survey indicators, Panorama SEL data, and behavioral data (office referrals, proactive check-ins, attendance). To support this, Keller will implement family partnership practices that elevate Black parent voice, including co-constructing what belonging looks like and sounds like and creating opportunities for families to share experiences that inform school practices. Data from Black family feedback will be used to co-design at least two schoolwide initiatives to improve student belonging and agency.
content.focus_area: Elevating Parent Voice of Black Students through Family Engagement
content.strategies_summarized: Helen Keller Elementary will establish a Parent Equity Team and Teacher Equity Team to co-construct what belonging looks like with Black families and use their feedback to design schoolwide initiatives that improve student belonging and agency. The school will also partner with the "And Still We Rise" program and leverage a Harvard partnership with Dr. Karen Mapp through the Building Leadership Team to provide expert guidance and support for these equity-focused efforts. Additionally, whole staff professional development will be implemented to ensure all educators are equipped to support the social-emotional growth of Black/Black-Hispanic/Black two or more races students, with progress monitored through SEL survey indicators, Panorama data, and behavioral metrics including office referrals, proactive check-ins, and attendance.

content.strategies_summarized: Peter Kirk Elementary will implement a comprehensive Multi-Tiered System of Supports (MTSS) across Kindergarten through Grade 5, utilizing a three-tier approach that includes grade-level instruction with UFLI implementation for all students (Tier 1), data-directed small group instruction using evidence-based programs like Heggerty and UFLI with clear progress monitoring and exit criteria (Tier 2), and targeted instruction aligned with IEP goals and grade-level standards (Tier 3). To support these interventions, the school will establish dedicated professional learning partnerships with LWSD TOSAs to train staff on UFLI implementation, small group instruction, and inquiry-based mathematics practices, while also creating building-wide block schedules with aligned instructional and intervention blocks and streamlined classified schedules to maximize support. Progress toward the reading and math growth outcomes will be monitored through formal and informal observations of instruction, PLC meeting notes and student data protocols, coaching cycle documentation, and ongoing schedule adjustments to ensure all students receive the targeted supports needed to demonstrate typical or aggressive growth.

content.strategies_summarized: Peter Kirk Elementary will implement a comprehensive, multi-tiered approach to improve students' sense of belonging by delivering universal SEL instruction through counselor-led lessons and PurposeFull People activities (Tier 1), providing small-group skills-based interventions for identified students (Tier 2), and offering individualized counseling support (Tier 3). Additionally, the school will invest in professional learning for staff through TIES Center training, E-M-R training, and culturally responsive teaching workshops to ensure educators can create inclusive classroom communities, while expanding student leadership opportunities through WingMates peer mentoring, clubs, and school activities. The school will also strengthen community partnerships by collaborating with the PTSA to host inclusive recess activities and reinvigorate the parent volunteer Co-pilot program, creating multiple touchpoints for students to experience belonging and supportive relationships across school and home settings.

content.outcome: Close proficiency gap that currently exists between K/1st and 2-5 low-income students as measured by Fastbridge assessment (early reading for K-1 and aReading for 2-5).
content.strategies_summarized: Lakeview Elementary School will implement a comprehensive, multi-tiered literacy approach to close the proficiency gap between K/1st and 2-5 low-income students. At Tier 1, all students will receive daily explicit instruction using Wonders and UFLI/Heggerty (K-2), along with Lexia 2-3 times weekly, while being assessed three times yearly with Fastbridge to identify students needing additional support. For students with risk indicators or identified needs, the school will provide targeted Tier 2 and 3 small group instruction using differentiated resources, with progress monitored through collaborative PLC cycles, coaching cycles with the MTSS coach, and intervention team meetings held on 6-week rotation schedules. Additionally, literacy-focused professional development and learning walks facilitated by the MTSS coach will support teachers in implementing these strategies effectively across classrooms.
content.currentdata: According to Fall 2025 Fastbridge screener data: • 43% of students identified as low-income scored proficiently (low or minimal risk) on the earlyReading assessment with kindergarten and first grade students in comparison to 79% of students categorized as non-low- income. We saw • 59% of students identified as low-income scored proficiently (low or minimal risk) on the aReading assessment with 2nd-5th grade students in comparison to 89% of students categorized as non-low income. 13.2% of our total student population is low income. There is a disproportionate number of students identified as low income. There is also intersectionality of students receiving special education services and multilingual learners who also qualify for low income, further adding to the disproportionality. 24.6% of students identified as low income also receive special education services. 27.9% of students identified as low income are also multilingual learners.

content.strategies_summarized: Lakeview Elementary School will implement a comprehensive, multi-tiered approach to close the proficiency gap between K/1st and 2-5 low-income students by conducting three annual Fastbridge assessments to monitor progress, establishing consistent Tier 1 instruction through daily use of Illustrative Mathematics (IM) routines and Dreambox practice 2-3 days per week, and conducting twice-yearly reviews of pacing guides and essential lessons in grade-level PLC meetings. The school will simultaneously strengthen instructional quality through targeted professional development in mathematics content, standards unpacking, and Building Thinking Classrooms strategies, while identifying and implementing differentiated learning strategies informed by assessment data and collaborative analysis of student progress. Additionally, the MTSS Intervention Team will conduct six-week rotation cycles with documented progress monitoring and learning walks led by the MTSS coach to ensure consistent implementation and refinement of intervention strategies across all classrooms.

content.outcome: All students will improve how they manage challenging feelings from 67% to 78% as measured by panorama data, youth needs screener data, student reflection, and classroom observations.
content.strategies_summarized: Lakeview Elementary School will implement a comprehensive, multi-tiered approach to help all students improve their management of challenging feelings. At the Tier 1 level, the school will provide dedicated, explicit SEL instruction using the district-adopted Purposeful People curriculum, implement PBIS team-created lessons and student self-reflections focused on specific challenging emotions (mad, sad, worried, lonely), administer Character Strong and PBIS screeners twice yearly to all K-5 students, and ensure all teachers implement equity and inclusion-focused lessons and practices such as EMR and UDL through professional development. Additionally, the school will teach and regularly review schoolwide expectations, engage families through conferences and community SEL events, and support staff with professional development on belonging and inclusive practices. For students needing additional support, the school will provide Tier 2 targeted small group interventions with the counselor based on data from Panorama, screeners, Youth Needs assessments, and teacher/parent referrals, with progress monitored through MTSS Intervention Team meetings held in 6-week cycles and ongoing family-school communication.

content.strategies_summarized: To achieve 95% of students in grades 3–5 at or above standard in ELA by Spring 2028, Christa McAuliffe Elementary will implement a comprehensive, multi-faceted literacy improvement plan centered on data-driven instruction and professional development. Grade-level teams will analyze 2025 SBA target data to focus instruction on identified areas of weakness in reading and writing across all three grades, while all K–5 teachers will participate in collaborative discussions on writing instruction, implement culturally responsive teaching strategies, and engage in vertical teaming to ensure consistent organizational and revision support through graphic organizers and checklists. Additionally, the school will establish regular intervention block schedules, provide intensive professional development in evidence-based programs such as Heggerty, UFLI, Secret Stories, Lexia, and Writing Revolution strategies, calibrate grading and rubrics with Instructional Coach support, and ensure that special education, safety net, and multilingual staff are integrated into intervention scheduling to support all learners.
content.currentdata: Literacy goals were created based upon reading/writing teacher pre-assessment data, historical performance, developmental needs, and identification of students not at standard on state (SBA) and district (FastBridge) assessments. Additional consideration was given to areas on the SBA where students performed lower relative to other portions of the test, per target data information. Action items were created to support growth within these goal areas, providing challenge and rigor for all students, focusing on intervention efforts, and emphasizing collaboration amongst staff in support of all students in the area of Literacy.

content.outcome: 75% of students in grades 3 – 5 will respond favorably in Emotional Regulation as measured by the Panorama Survey in Spring of 2027.
content.strategies_summarized: To achieve 75% of students in grades 3–5 responding favorably in Emotional Regulation on the Spring 2027 Panorama Survey, Christa McAuliffe Elementary will implement a comprehensive, school-wide approach centered on teaching and reinforcing evidence-based strategies such as breathing techniques, Zones of Regulation, and Kelso's Choices across all settings. Teachers in grades K–5 will incorporate focused SEL instruction using the Purposeful People curriculum and Second Steps lessons, while simultaneously establishing classroom supports including calm-down corners, sensory tools, and explicit vocabulary instruction aligned with the survey. Additionally, the school will engage school counselors, classified staff, and families through professional development on de-escalation strategies, monthly parent communication about home-based practices, and visual supports displayed throughout the building and playground, with progress monitored through regular administrator check-ins and staff participation data.

Sub-questions within Emotional Regulation: How often are you able to pull yourself out of a bad mood? • 2024: 55% favorable • 2025: 62% favorable (+7%) When things go wrong for you, how calm are you able to stay? • 2024: 49% favorable • 2025: 63% favorable (+14%) Once you get upset, how often can you get yourself to relax?

content.strategies_summarized: Margaret Mead Elementary School will implement a comprehensive phonemic awareness initiative for kindergarten and 1st grade students by establishing daily Heggerty instruction (10-15 minutes) in collaboration with the Safety Net teacher, utilizing explicit phonics lesson sequences during Wonders whole group instruction, and providing tier 2 small group differentiated instruction supported by curricular tools such as the Instructional Routine Handbook, SIPPS, UFLI, and Wonder Works. Additionally, the school will leverage FastBridge/SBA assessment data to monitor student growth at key checkpoints (BOY, MOY, EOY) and adjust instruction accordingly, while ensuring that Special Education teachers coordinate pull-out and push-in services during core instruction and intervention blocks. Administrative support will include assigning IA support during daily intervention blocks, setting clear expectations around curricular systems, and facilitating Multi Lingual support for qualifying students to ensure all kindergarten and 1st grade students receive consistent, research-based phonemic awareness instruction.

content.outcome: 85% of students in grades 3 – 5 will be at or above standard in Mathematics as measured by the Smarter Balanced Assessment in Spring, 2028.
content.strategies_summarized: Margaret Mead Elementary School will achieve the goal of 85% of students in grades 3–5 meeting or exceeding mathematics standards on the Spring 2028 Smarter Balanced Assessment through a comprehensive, multi-faceted approach. Grade level teams will analyze spring 2025 SBA and FastBridge data to identify students below standard and monitor their progress throughout the year via BOY, MOY, and EOY assessments. To strengthen instructional practices, teachers in grades K–5 will participate in vertical and horizontal teaming through LEAP to master the math curriculum and ensure students receive exposure to critical late-spring units before the assessment. Additionally, the school will provide daily grade-level intervention blocks with teacher-led small groups and IA support, align special education pull-out and push-in instruction during core math instruction, establish clear and consistent expectations around curricular systems across all grade levels, and maintain regular communication with families about grade-level curriculum to support student success.

content.outcome: By spring, 2028, in the Panorama Survey category of Emotional Regulation, 65% or more of students in grades 3 – 5 will respond favorably in Emotional Regulation as measured by the Panorama Survey.
content.strategies_summarized: Margaret Mead Elementary School will implement a comprehensive, multi-faceted approach to improve emotional regulation in grades 3-5, beginning with data analysis of the Panorama Survey to identify specific areas of need and raise staff awareness. The school will support schoolwide implementation of the Purposeful People program integrated with PBIS and MTSS efforts, emphasizing emotional regulation lessons and monthly traits through announcements and video displays, while simultaneously establishing a PBIS positive affirmation system across classrooms and the building to reinforce positive behavior choices. Additionally, the school will establish calm down corners in each classroom with explicit instruction on their use, incorporate mindfulness technology tools such as GoNoodle and Cosmic Kids Yoga, and explore the purchase of Purposeful People Tier 2 curriculum for targeted counselor lessons and special education intervention groups.

content.strategies_summarized: John Muir Elementary School will implement a comprehensive literacy initiative centered on the University of Florida Literacy Institute curriculum through multiple coordinated actions, including providing new staff training on CORE Reading Fundamentals and ongoing professional learning in phonemic awareness, phonics, foundational reading practices, and Visible Learning strategies to strengthen collective efficacy across grade levels. The school will ensure daily 10-15 minute instructional blocks for Heggerty and phonics in all K-3 classrooms, leverage Safety Net staff to support implementation through small-group instruction and co-teaching, and develop consistent, systematic, and explicit Tier 1 reading practices across all classrooms to support all learners, including those receiving multilingual and special education services. To maintain quality and effectiveness, the school will conduct regular fidelity checks of Tier 1 practices to monitor implementation and alignment with schoolwide reading goals.

content.outcome: By Spring 2026, students in grades K-5, will improve by at least one proficiency level or maintain grade-level proficiency in Numbers and Operations, measured by grade-level Common District Summative Assessments.
content.strategies_summarized: John Muir Elementary School will strengthen instructional practices in Numbers and Operations through comprehensive professional learning in Building Thinking Classrooms, DreamBox strategies, and Visible Learning, while simultaneously implementing structured instructional changes including math small groups, Illustrative Mathematics Centers, and dedicated small-group math time integrated into the master schedule. The school will establish consistent, equitable Tier 1 math practices across all classrooms and conduct regular fidelity checks and cycles of inquiry focused on place value to ensure vertical alignment of standards and support student discourse and problem-solving. These coordinated efforts in teacher development, instructional design, and systematic support structures are designed to help all students in grades K-5 improve by at least one proficiency level or maintain grade-level proficiency in Numbers and Operations by Spring 2026.

content.outcome: By June 2028, the percentage of students in grades 3–5 who demonstrate emotional regulation will increase from 46% to 54%, as measured by schoolwide SEL data from Panorama.
content.strategies_summarized: To achieve this outcome, John Muir Elementary School will provide comprehensive professional learning on the Zones of Regulation curriculum to all staff, including instructional assistants and paraprofessionals, while simultaneously piloting the program with a small teacher team to refine strategies before full schoolwide implementation. The school will establish common SEL routines, visuals, and vocabulary throughout the building and create Zones-aligned learning environments supported by regular fidelity checks to ensure consistent, high-quality implementation across all settings. Additionally, the school will implement tiered systems of support including Tier 2 social-emotional groups focused on emotional regulation, Check-In/Check-Out systems for student monitoring and connection, and the 10×10 system to proactively support student well-being, while providing ongoing professional learning centered on Visible Learning practices, professional learning communities, and equity.

content.outcome: All students will meet literacy benchmarks by spring of 2026 as measured by Fastbridge in the areas that measure phonemic awareness, phonics and fluency.
content.focus_area: Implementation of UFLI instructional practices and materials to support our students in the areas of Phonics and Fluency.
content.strategies_summarized: Norman Rockwell Elementary School will implement the UFLI (Unified Foundational Literacy Instruction) program across all K-2 classrooms by providing comprehensive training to teachers, instructional assistants, special needs teachers, and instructional coaches, followed by a full coaching cycle to ensure fidelity. The school will conduct monthly fidelity checks focusing on core routines, pacing, and lesson structure, analyze progress-monitoring data every six weeks to adjust instructional groups, and deliver daily UFLI-aligned phonics instruction with consistent pacing. Implementation will be monitored through PD attendance logs, coaching cycle notes, monthly walkthrough tool data, updated intervention rosters, lesson plan reviews, and regular admin and coach classroom walkthroughs to track progress toward the literacy benchmarks.

content.outcome: 70% of students will show typical or aggressive growth from Fall to Spring as measured by the FastBridge Mathematics screener by Spring 2026.
content.strategies_summarized: To achieve 70% of students showing typical or aggressive growth on the FastBridge Mathematics screener by Spring 2026, Rosa Parks Elementary will implement a comprehensive, multi-tiered approach to mathematics instruction and intervention. All students will receive core mathematics instruction in their general education classrooms with supplemental Tier II interventions provided through intervention block time and small group strategies, while teachers use pre-assessments and "cool downs" to monitor understanding and target instruction. Additionally, teachers will engage in Professional Learning Communities focused on cycles of inquiry, participate in professional learning around UDL strategies and access points for complexity, and utilize research-based practices including IM center activities, math games, Dreambox adaptive software, and small group structures to provide differentiated learning and additional practice opportunities for all students.
content.currentdata: Data: In the period from Fall 2022-Spring 2023, the mean by grade for students measuring typical or aggressive growth for the school was 57%. Typical growth is defined as falling in the 40th to 75th percentile, and aggressive growth is defined as 75th percentile or higher based on FastBridge. This measure is produced by the Group Growth Report, measuring Fall to Spring, based on comparing students’ median growth rate to median growth rate of students in the same grade nationally who started at the same score. Update: In the Fall 2023-Spring 2024 period, the mean by grade for students measuring typical or aggressive growth for the school was 55%. Update in Fall 2024-Spring 2025, the mean by grade for students measuring typical or aggressive growth for the school was 52%. We are struggling with this goal. While the achievement rate on FastBridge for our school remains high with 85% of students meeting or exceeding expected scores on the assessment, growth with this tool is a challenge. It’s important to note that Classroom-based measures show higher growth. There is some doubt in the FastBridge measurement tool among staff. Rationale: We want all students to grow in their learning. By measuring growth rate, we can monitor the progress of both students who are already achieving at high levels and need challenge as well as students who need support and intervention to meet benchmarks ensuring that students are making personal
content.engagement_strategies: In their classroom newsletters, teachers will share math learning targets for each Illustrative Mathematics (IM) Unit, the family connection letter for each unit, as well as send strategies and resources to support math learning at home. They will also engage families through twice-a-year conferences and individual communications with families as needed. Schoolwide communications will occur through the weekly Puma Press newsletter, an annual family feedback survey, and well as parent participation on school committees (Equity, Safety, Special Education Advisory, etc…). We also work closely and collaboratively with our PTSA. Increased communication about student goals and student growth progress.

content.outcome: 75% of students will show typical or aggressive growth from Fall to Spring as measured by the FastBridge Reading screener Group Growth Report by Spring 2026.
content.strategies_summarized: Rosa Parks Elementary will implement a comprehensive, multi-tiered reading intervention approach to achieve 75% typical or aggressive growth by Spring 2026, utilizing daily differentiated small group instruction in all classrooms guided by FastBridge and classroom-based data to target foundational skills gaps. Teachers will deliver systematic, evidence-based instruction through core curricula including Heggerty phonemic awareness and UFli phonics in grades K-2, supported by professional learning communities, specialized teacher collaboration, and professional development focused on UDL strategies and intervention techniques. Additional support will be provided through Safety Net and multi-lingual teachers, instructional assistants, and Lexia adaptive software, with fidelity monitored through master schedule implementation, staff training completion, and ongoing progress monitoring measures.
content.currentdata: Data: In the period from Fall 2022-Spring 2023, the mean by grade level for students measuring typical or aggressive growth for the school was 67%. Typical growth is defined as falling in the 40th to 75th percentile and aggressive growth is defined as 75th percentile or higher on FastBridge. This measure is produced by the Group Growth Report, measuring Fall to Spring, based on comparing student’s median growth rate to median growth rate of students in the same grade nationally who started at the same score. Update: In the Fall 2023-Spring 2024 period, the mean by grade for students measuring typical or aggressive growth for the school was 54%. Update: In the Fall 2024-Spring 2025 period, the mean by grade for students measuring typical or aggressive growth for the school was 56%. We are struggling with this goal. While the achievement rate on FastBridge for our school remains high with 87% of students meeting or exceeding expected scores on the assessment, growth with this tool is a challenge. We’ve made small progress since last year. It’s important to note that Classroom-based measures show higher growth. There is some doubt about the FastBridge measurement tool among staff. Rationale: We want all students to grow in their learning. By measuring growth rate, we can monitor the progress of both students who are already achieving at high levels and need challenge as well as students who need support and intervention to meet benchmarks ensuring that students are making personal progress in their learning wherever they begin on the continuum. A growth measure is an important indicator of meeting the needs of all students. We are a high achieving school, and most students are meeting expected standards, but we want them to make a year’s growth even if they are already at standard.

content.outcome: 78% of all students will be able to regulate their emotions according to self-perception data as recorded by the Panorama survey data (grades 3-5) and through teacher data from the BEISY screener (K-5) by Spring 2026.
content.strategies_summarized: Rosa Parks Elementary will implement a comprehensive, school-wide approach to emotional regulation through the adoption of the Zones of Regulation framework, establishment of calming corners in all classrooms, and explicit instruction of self-regulation strategies across all grade levels. Teachers will receive professional learning and model self-regulation techniques while utilizing positive reinforcement through PUMAS tickets and teachable moments, supported by universal SEL visuals, Character Strong curriculum, counselor-led lessons and small groups, and age-appropriate SEL books integrated into instruction. Additionally, the school will provide targeted interventions for students needing extra support through student support teams, scheduled motor lab sessions, professional development for instructional assistants in de-escalation strategies, and a Kindergarten-focused cycle of inquiry to build these foundational skills early, with progress monitored through teacher observations, staff self-reflection, BEISY Screener data, and the Panorama survey.
content.currentdata: At the beginning of the 2022-2023 school year, 52% of students responded favorably on the Panorama survey when prompted to rate their ability to regulate their emotions. This overall percentage is lower than the beginning of the 2018-2019 school year at 54%. With focused, strategic, and school-wide instruction, we believe we can significantly increase students’ abilities to self- regulate their emotions. 2023-2024 update: In Spring 2024, 58% of students who took the Panorama survey responded favorably when prompted to rate their ability to regulate their emotions. Fall 2024 BEISY data: On the BEISY screener, teachers indicated 15% of students at risk for Externalizing Behaviors and 10% at risk for internalizing behaviors, suggesting 85% and 90% respectively are meeting SEL expectations.
content.engagement_strategies: Teachers and counselor will communicate what Character Strong and SEL Skills are being taught in class lessons. Teachers and the school will communicate about goals and challenges in newsletters to families, seeking volunteers for recess and classroom support, etc. They will also engage families through twice-a-year conferences and individual communications with families as needed. Schoolwide communications will occur through the weekly Puma Press newsletter, an annual family feedback survey, and well as parent participation on school committees (Equity, Safety, Special Education Advisory, etc…). We also work closely and collaboratively with our PTSA.

content.strategies_summarized: Rose Hill Elementary will implement a comprehensive mathematics program focusing on building foundational number sense in kindergarten through concrete experiences, introducing operations within 20, and strengthening mathematical vocabulary and language. The school will establish strong place value understanding through 120 and develop problem-solving skills using multiple representations, including connections to fractions and decimals with emphasis on justification. To support these initiatives, the school will utilize professional learning community data conversations, common planning among grade levels, classroom-based assessments, teacher observations, and progress monitoring to ensure student mastery and guide instructional adjustments.

content.strategies_summarized: Benjamin Rush Elementary School will implement a comprehensive, multi-tiered literacy approach to achieve one year of reading growth for all students as measured by FastBridge data. At the Tier 1 level, the school will establish strong foundational literacy instruction through whole-class implementation of Heggerty phonemic awareness instruction (10-15 minutes daily in K-2 classrooms), explicit phonics lessons within the Wonders curriculum, and UFLi curriculum in kindergarten, with fidelity monitoring of classroom adherence to these programs. For students demonstrating risk indicators, the school will provide differentiated small group instruction through Tier 2 supports via the UFLi curriculum in general education classrooms with Safety Net teacher collaboration, specialized instruction through Safety Net and Multilingual Learner programs, and for students with identified special education needs, specialized instruction through the Special Education Program. Additionally, the school will provide professional learning to K-2 teachers on strong foundation literacy instruction and UFLi curriculum implementation to ensure high-quality delivery of all reading interventions.

content.strategies_summarized: Benjamin Rush Elementary School will implement a multi-tiered approach to increase peer connections and reduce the percentage of students lacking a friend they can count on from 18% to below 10%. At the Tier 1 level, teachers will implement the 4 at the door strategy from Purposefull People, with implementation tracked by the number of participating teachers. For Tier 2 support, the school will interview identified students with low peer or staff connections during winter and spring to gather street data, while simultaneously offering optional alternative recess activities organized around shared interests to encourage peer engagement among this group. Additionally, Tier 3 interventions will utilize the 2x10 relation-building strategy for sub-group families, with progress measured by the number of students who complete this intensive intervention.

content.strategies_summarized: Carl Sandburg Elementary School will implement a comprehensive, multi-tiered reading intervention approach to achieve this outcome, beginning with whole-class Heggerty phonemic awareness instruction in Kindergarten through 2nd grade (10-15 minutes daily) in collaboration with Safety Net teachers, while incorporating explicit phonics and phonemic awareness into daily Wonders whole group instruction as observed during administrative walkthroughs. Additionally, the school will provide targeted Tier 2 small group differentiated instruction for students showing risk indicators in phonemic awareness, phonics, and fluency using Wonders curricular resources and FastBridge intervention plans with progress monitoring, supplemented by small group instruction using the UFLI curriculum with documented group rosters and lesson plans to ensure all students receive appropriate support based on their individual needs.
content.currentdata: Preventing any student in grades K-2 from demonstrating high risk on the FastBridge End of Year assessments allows for early identification and targeted intervention. This proactive approach helps address reading difficulties before they become more entrenched, reducing long-term learning gaps. Monitoring growth through the Screening to Intervention Report ensures that instruction is responsive and tailored to each student’s needs, promoting equitable learning opportunities.

content.strategies_summarized: Carl Sandburg Elementary School will review FastBridge growth data during winter to identify student strengths and weaknesses, then update their watch list with current data to address students' evolving needs. The school will implement flexible small group instruction during WINN 1 and WINN 2 sessions using targeted FastBridge resources and evidence-based strategies such as guided practice, modeling, and multi-sensory instruction, while also providing clear success criteria for assignments, peer tutoring opportunities, and personalized engagement to help fifth-grade students achieve a median growth percentile of 60 or greater on the Spring 2026 ELA SBA.
content.currentdata: When students get to middle school, there is a huge shift to reading to learn, versus learning to read. Our current data shows that students grew by a median growth percentile of 51 on the Spring 2025 ELA SBA, 49 on the Spring 2024 ELA SBA and 57on the Spring 2023 ELA SBA. This means that just about half of our students are growing less than their peers of the same age with similar score profiles throughout the state. This same data trend is also evident in FastBridge Growth Percentile data from the 2024- 2025 school year.

content.outcome: By Spring 2026, 95% of 3rd grade students will meet or exceed grade-level literacy proficiency as measured by the FastBridge Screening to Intervention (S2i) Report. This goal mirrors the Lake Washington School District Key Performance Indicator that all students will be literate by the end of 3rd grade. It reflects the cumulative impact of K–3 instruction and intervention systems designed to ensure that every student develops strong foundational reading skills in decoding, fluency, and comprehension.
content.strategies_summarized: Samantha Smith Elementary School will implement a comprehensive, multi-tiered literacy system to achieve 95% of 3rd grade students meeting grade-level proficiency by Spring 2026. The school will deliver explicit, systematic Tier 1 instruction using evidence-based programs (Wonders, UFLI, Heggerty) while using FastBridge screening data to identify at-risk students and monitor progress through regular MTSS team reviews. Students requiring additional support will receive targeted Tier 2 small-group instruction supported by Lexia Core5, with consistent IA and interventionist schedules ensuring equitable access, while staff will dedicate time to data analysis, professional learning in structured literacy practices, and collaboration with district specialists to continuously refine instructional practices and adjust supports based on progress-monitoring data.

content.outcome: By Spring 2026, 95% of 5th grade students will meet or exceed grade-level math proficiency as measured by the FastBridge Screening to Intervention (S2i) Report. This goal mirrors the Lake Washington School District Key Performance Indicator that all students will be successful in mathematics by the end of 5th grade. The outcome represents the collective work of all K–5 teachers in building conceptual understanding, problem-solving, and fluency through consistent Tier 1 instruction and targeted supports within the MTSS framework.
content.strategies_summarized: Samantha Smith Elementary School will implement a comprehensive, multi-tiered approach to achieve 95% math proficiency by Spring 2026, beginning with consistent Tier 1 instruction using Illustrative Math across all classrooms while incorporating Building Thinking Classrooms strategies to enhance engagement and mathematical reasoning. The school will dedicate LEAP and staff meeting time to collaborative lesson planning and data analysis, supported by district math facilitators through instructional coaching, while using FastBridge aMath/earlyMath and classroom formative assessments to identify at-risk students for targeted Tier 2 interventions delivered through strategic IA support and adaptive tools like DreamBox. Progress will be monitored through regular MTSS-I meetings and data reflection cycles facilitated by the MTSS Leadership Team and Intervention Team, ensuring that instructional adjustments are made based on student growth and emerging needs.

content.outcome: By Spring 2026, at least 80% of students will be able to identify and effectively apply at least one self-regulation strategy to help themselves return to the Green Zone, as demonstrated through classroom activities, teacher observations, student reflections, or use during everyday classroom situations that require emotional regulation (e.g., transitions, peer interactions, or moments of frustration).
content.strategies_summarized: Samantha Smith Elementary School will implement a comprehensive, multi-tiered approach to teach students self-regulation strategies aligned with the Zones of Regulation framework. Core instruction will be delivered through Zones of Regulation and Purposeful People lessons taught by classroom teachers and the school counselor, with all general education classrooms equipped with emotional regulation spaces and tools to support student practice. Additionally, the school will provide targeted interventions including small group instruction, LINKS mentorships, and individual Check-In and Check-Out systems for students needing additional support, with the PBIS & SEL work team, MTSS Leadership Team, and MTSS Intervention Team coordinating these efforts and monitoring progress through lesson plans, classroom walkthroughs, Tier 2 intervention data, and team meeting notes.

content.strategies_summarized: Thoreau Elementary will achieve this reading growth outcome through a multifaceted approach centered on building strong family-school partnerships and delivering high-quality, culturally responsive literacy instruction. Teachers will establish connection meetings with families to inform individualized student growth goals focused on literacy, while the school will create community-building opportunities such as summer library hours, book fairs, and reading nights to engage families and encourage volunteers to support classroom reading instruction. Additionally, the school will implement a structured literacy block featuring high-quality Tier I instruction supported by professional learning communities engaged in cycles of inquiry, complemented by daily small group instruction in flexible groups with targeted skill development and dedicated instructional assistant support in grades K-2.

content.outcome: By June 2025, each grade level at Mark Twain Elementary will demonstrate measurable growth in reading proficiency, as evidenced by EarlyReading (K–1) and AReading (grades 2–5) benchmark assessments. Specifically: • Grades currently below 80% proficiency (K: 75%, 1st: 79%, 2nd: 66%, 3rd: 75%, 5th: 69%) will show a minimum 10 percentage point increase in the percentage of students meeting or exceeding grade- level benchmarks. • Grades already above 80% proficiency (4th:90%) will maintain or improve their performance, ensuring continued excellence in reading achievement. This outcome reflects the school’s commitment to equitable academic growth, targeted support, and sustained high performance across all grade levels.
content.focus_area: Reading proficiency across grade levels is part of a broader focus on academic achievement and instructional effectiveness in literacy, tied to LWSD priorities.
content.strategies_summarized: To achieve measurable growth in reading proficiency across all grade levels by June 2025, Mark Twain Elementary will establish protected, uninterrupted blocks of daily Tier 1 reading instruction while implementing consistent Tier 2 interventions four times per week for students below grade-level benchmarks and targeted Tier 2 and 3 small-group sessions for those requiring intensive support. The school will employ a collaborative approach through weekly common planning and six- to eight-week data teaming cycles, where grade-level teams analyze progress monitoring data (collected every six weeks, with bi-weekly monitoring for students not meeting benchmarks) and adjust instruction accordingly, while ensuring multilingual learners receive integrated language support through co-teaching models and students are not pulled from core instruction except as outlined in IEPs. These multi-tiered interventions, coupled with consistent assessment and responsive instruction, will ensure that grades currently below 80% proficiency demonstrate a minimum 10 percentage point increase while maintaining the excellence in grades already meeting proficiency targets.

content.outcome: By June 2025, Mark Twain Elementary will strengthen staff- student relationships to meet or exceed district averages as measured by Panorama surveys. Specifically, we will increase student confidence that staff care when they are upset and by at least 10 percentage points and reverse the 11% decline since 2021. Additionally, we will increase how difficult it is to find help from an adult if a student is bullied by at least 10 percentage points.
content.strategies_summarized: To strengthen staff-student relationships and address bullying concerns, Mark Twain Elementary will increase adult visibility and responsiveness by scheduling classified staff to monitor high-risk areas throughout the day, supported by weekly walkthroughs and a daily supervision checklist, while all classified staff will receive training on immediate response protocols to ensure quick and supportive action when students seek help. Additionally, the school will teach anti-bullying strategies through weekly SEL lessons at each grade level focused on empathy, kindness, and practical tools for addressing bullying, while the administrative team reviews incident data weekly to track patterns and identify training needs. The school will also implement Tier 2 interventions delivered by the school counselor for students identified through benchmark assessments and Panorama survey results, focusing on social-emotional skills and conflict resolution with progress monitored through pre- and post-assessments, and will conduct grade-level data cycles every 6-8 weeks and quarterly student interviews to ensure students feel heard and supported.

content.strategies_summarized: Laura Ingalls Wilder Elementary School will implement a comprehensive literacy improvement plan to achieve these proficiency benchmarks across all grade levels. The school will provide professional development in comprehension during LEAP time while teachers participate in Professional Learning Communities to analyze student progress and adjust instruction accordingly. Additionally, the school will establish whole group instruction in Heggerty Phonics for preschool through second grade, implement UFLI phonemic awareness instruction in kindergarten through second grade, and utilize a tiered instructional approach with dedicated core instructional time and power blocks to provide targeted Tier 1, 2, and 3 instruction based on student needs. content.strategies_summarized: Laura Ingalls Wilder Elementary School will implement a comprehensive, multi-layered approach to improve emotional regulation among students in grades 3-5. The school will establish consistent daily SEL and restorative circles across all classrooms while creating accessible regulation spaces, a schoolwide sensory path, and a sensory gym to support student self-regulation. Additionally, the MTSS Tier 2/3 Intervention Team will meet monthly to develop and monitor tiered interventions, the school will implement a schoolwide PBIS program through whole staff collaboration, and the counselor will deliver targeted small-group and whole-group lessons using the Zones of Regulation curriculum, with progress monitored through pre/post assessments and discipline data.
content.currentdata: In the Spring of 2025 60% of students responded favorably on Emotion Regulation as measured by Panorama. Dr. Richie Davidson (University of Wisconsin-Madison) speaks about ‘every behavioral intervention being a biological intervention’—and that a young person’s repeated experiences in school have the opportunity to be a powerful influence for the re- wiring of neural pathways that is necessary for habits to be built and sustained. Implementing and sustaining a consistent set of SEL practices helps stakeholders collaboratively create the climate and culture that’s vital for optimal learning and working conditions for students and adults (CASEL, 2024). While SEL alone will not solve longstanding and deep-seated inequities in the education system, it can help schools promote understanding, examine biases, reflect on and address the impact of racism, build cross-cultural relationships, and cultivate adult and student practices that close opportunity gaps and create a more inclusive school community. In doing so, schools can promote high-quality educational opportunities and outcomes for all students, irrespective of race, socioeconomic status, gender, sexual orientation, and other differences. This requires that SEL is implemented with an explicit goal of promoting educational equity (CASEL, 2024).
