content.strategies_summarized: The Environmental & Adventure School will develop common journal prompts through staff collaboration and assessment, enabling students to reflect on their community stewardship projects and expedition experiences. Students will engage in self-assessment by documenting their reflections on these experiences, while families will participate in guided reflection, discussion, and written responses about their student's adventures and learning. Additionally, fall and winter conferences will provide structured opportunities for students, families, and teachers to collectively discuss camp and community stewardship experiences and reflect on the journaling process, creating meaningful connections between school experiences and family engagement.
content.currentdata: Over the past several years, EAS has experienced a decrease in the number of families involved in supporting school activities by driving, chaperoning, or leading Wednesday Elective sessions and/or after-school clubs. Specifically with CSPs and Adventure Education trips, only a limited number of parents/guardians can attend. Because community stewardship and adventure education are pillars of EAS as a school, the EAS staff sought out additional ways to engage families in these critical components of our school. EAS staff agreed that sharing CSP and expedition journaling with families was not only a good jumping-off point for discussions at home, but also a way to amplify student voice in the discussion. The goal is to have… • 100% family participation in CSP Journal communication and Expedition Journal communication. • An increase in family involvement from the student’s 6th grade year to their 8th grade year
content.engagement_strategies: • School-home communication via CSP and Expedition Journals • ParentSquare communication • Fall and winter conferences

content.strategies_summarized: Kamiakin Middle School will implement a comprehensive, multi-faceted approach to improve student literacy by providing professional development to teachers on evidence-based reading strategies, including the Improving Reading for Secondary Students curriculum, Target 11 strategies, and culturally responsive teaching practices through the Hess Rigor Matrix. The school will conduct biweekly literacy screenings through Power Up for Literacy and deliver targeted reading interventions through Flex classes and a dedicated Reading Intervention Class with explicit comprehension strategies and frequent progress monitoring for struggling readers. Additionally, co-teaching partnerships between special education and mainstream teachers, along with a world language reading strategy focus, will ensure that all students, including multilingual learners, receive consistent reading support across content areas.
content.currentdata: 64% of our 8th graders this year met standard on the English Language Arts Smarter Balanced Assessment in the spring of 2025. SBA Strand data shows that our 7th graders last year had the greatest opportunity for growth in: Reading Informational text, Target 11: REASONING & EVIDENCE: Make an inference or draw a conclusion about a text OR make inferences or draw conclusions in order to compare texts (e.g., interaction between individuals, events and ideas; author’s point of view/purpose; use of media or formats; trace and evaluate the argument and specific claims) and use supporting evidence as justification/explanation.

content.outcome: By May 2026, students’ general academic self-efficacy scores on the Panorama Survey will increase by at least 5% from the 2025 results, as measured by the Self-Efficacy domain. Self-efficacy is the belief in one’s ability to succeed in specific situations or accomplish a task, significantly influencing motivation, behavior and personal achievement. It is essentially the confidence one has in their ability to influence events and control their environment. We want to provide our students with evidence that they have the ability to meet our high academic expectations.
content.strategies_summarized: Kamiakin Middle School will implement frequent common formative assessments and self-assessment opportunities across content areas, with Teacher Professional Learning Communities documenting and sharing these practices to provide students with concrete evidence of their academic progress. Additionally, the school will provide explicit, school-wide instruction in executive functioning skills (including self-control, self-monitoring, emotional control, flexibility, task initiation, organization, working memory, and planning and time management) during Cougar Time, classes, and Flex Planning Time, supported by teacher reflection through the Instructional Leadership Team. To support these efforts, the school will engage staff in professional development on Danielson best practices and culturally responsive teaching, evaluated through LEAP presentation assessments and Panorama surveys on culturally responsive practices, while also ensuring that students with IEPs understand and can articulate their own goals by spring, as monitored through case manager assessments.
content.currentdata: Panorama Survey Data, Counselor Needs Assessment survey and Student Listening Session comments from 24-25 reveal this as a growth opportunity. Panorama: Trend Panorama survey data for the past years shows that we have not made the overall consistent positive progress that we have made in some of the other categories in recent years; such as supportive relationships, positive feelings, emotion regulation, social perspective taking. We started some professional development on self-efficacy in the 24-25 school year and did make significant (4% points) progress since the Fall 2024 survey. We want to build on this progress. Panorama data from Spring 2025 shows that this area continues to show the greatest gap with students who identify as Hispanic/Latino (of any race) and/or Black African American. These students combined self-report 25% less favorable self- efficacy as our other racial and ethnic groups. This area also contains the 3rd greatest disparity for our male and female students with our female students reporting a 9% less favorable response. content.outcome: On the Spring 2026 Math Smarter Balanced Assessment (SBA), 100% of 8th grade classes will demonstrate “above the proficiency standard” or “at/near the proficiency standard” on Target E: Define, Evaluate, and Compare Functions.
content.strategies_summarized: Kirkland Middle School will implement a comprehensive, multi-faceted approach to ensure all 8th grade students demonstrate proficiency in defining, evaluating, and comparing functions. The school will enhance instruction through Algebra I team collaboration focused on functions instruction, supplementation of curricula across Functions, Linear Functions, Quadratic Functions, and Exponential Functions units, and explicit teaching using multiple representations (equations, tables, graphs, and function notation), while also incorporating rich real-world tasks that promote mathematical discourse. Additionally, the school will provide targeted support through Academic Prep sessions, push-in interventionist support for Safety Net students in designated Algebra classes, a concurrent small math support class for identified students, a school-wide weekly problem-solving challenge featuring function-based problems, and a peer mentoring program, while Geometry students will also review functions throughout the year to reinforce these critical skills.
content.currentdata: Spring 2025 SBA Results – Math Target E, Grade 8 Mathematics Grade 8 – Class of 2029 3 out of 12 classes scored “above the proficiency standard”, 4 classes scored “at/near the proficiency standard”, and 6 classes scored “below the proficiency standard”. As a grade level, our performance on this target as compared to others was identified as an “area of weakness”. Additionally, the following classes showed that target was an “area of weakness” compared to the other targets: • 2 classes that scored “above the proficiency standard”, • 3 classes that scored “at/near the proficiency standard”, and • 5 of the classes that scored “below the proficiency standard”. Additional rationale for this focus: Functions form the foundation of algebraic thinking and are central to success in Algebra I and will be utilized in subsequent math courses. Strengthening students’ ability to define, evaluate, and compare functions supports the transition from arithmetic and proportional reasoning to more abstract reasoning about relationships and quantities. It also supports students identifying the connections between equations, tables, graphs, and descriptions of functions – skills required for modeling real-world situations and data interpretation.

content.strategies_summarized: To increase student reported self-efficacy by 6% on the Panorama Survey, Kirkland Middle School will implement a comprehensive, multi-faceted approach that embeds self-efficacy instruction throughout the school community. The school will integrate self-efficacy lessons focused on mindset and skills into Panther Time, provide professional learning to staff on self-efficacy theory and classroom strategies, and support teachers in incorporating these practices into their daily instruction through PLCs and classroom observations. Additionally, the school will monitor progress through monthly student surveys and individual self-efficacy check-ins during Student Success Meetings, using the collected data to adjust instruction and inform staff of student perceptions.
content.currentdata: Self-efficacy is one’s belief in their ability to complete specific tasks. These beliefs directly shape how students approach learning. When students believe they will be successful, they are willing to attempt challenging tasks, take intellectual risks, persist through difficulty, and recover from setbacks. When students have low self-efficacy, even students who are capable avoid rigorous work and give up quickly. By intentionally building student self-efficacy, we will teach and empower students to approach their learning with confidence, embrace rigor, and grow into resilient self-directed learners.

content.outcome: As measured by the Smarter Balanced Assessment (SBA), the proficiency of 8th grade students will improve from ‘weak’ in the 2024-25 school year to ‘strong’ in the 2025-26 school year for Target 8, Informational Text: “Given an inference or conclusion, use explicit details and implicit information from the text to support the inference or conclusion provided.”
content.strategies_summarized: Renaissance School of Arts and Reasoning will implement a multi-faceted approach to improve 8th grade students' ability to support inferences with textual evidence on the SBA. Teachers will incorporate close-reading routines such as annotating key details and identifying evidence when working with informational texts, while also regularly modeling their thinking by "talking through" how they make inferences and choose supporting details before guiding students in practicing the same process. Additionally, during novel studies in ELA, students will explain what details in the text help them infer about characters, themes, or events. To ensure consistency and effectiveness across these strategies, ELA teachers will share samples of student responses and discussion notes, periodically review student work to confirm close-reading routines are effective across subject areas, and document that think-alouds and guided practice are being used consistently.
content.currentdata: There are three targets on the 2024-25 SBA in which 8th grade students at RSAR achieved ‘weak’ proficiency, including Target 8. A weakly proficient score on this target indicates that students struggle to use details from a text to support an inference. Building this skill will help students understand what they read in all subjects, not just ELA. Moving from ‘weak’ to ‘strong’ proficiency will better prepare students for the tougher reading and thinking tasks they will face in high school.

content.outcome: To better prepare students for Algebra 1 as 7th or 8th graders, the percentage of 6th grade students earning scores of proficient or better on the Smarter Balanced Assessment (SBA) will improve from 61% in the 2024-25 school year to 75% in the 2025-26 school year.
content.focus_area: Math Fluency to support Algebra Readiness
content.strategies_summarized: Renaissance School of Arts and Reasoning will implement a comprehensive three-pronged approach to improve 6th grade math proficiency on the SBA from 61% to 75%. First, all students will engage in weekly math fluency activities targeting core prerequisite skills, with teachers documenting these activities through weekly logs and lesson plan integration. Additionally, students identified as needing support will participate in small-group math interventions during designated intervention periods, with progress tracked through attendance records and monitoring tools. Finally, students will reflect monthly on their math progress using journals or digital goal-setting tools, with teachers reviewing these reflections quarterly and incorporating them into student-led conferences to foster ownership of learning and accountability.
content.currentdata: Smarter Balanced Assessment (SBA) scores show 61% of 6th grade students showing scores of proficient or better in the 2024- 25 school year. FastBridge assessments reveal gaps in foundational math skills (e.g., multiplication, fractions). Struggles with basic fluency impact students’ ability to engage with more complex math concepts. Math anxiety is prevalent, and lack of fluency contributes to low confidence.
content.engagement_strategies: The School Improvement Plan is shaped by ongoing feedback from families and teachers, who consistently identify writing fluency, math fluency, and emotional regulation as top areas of need for students in middle school. These insights directly inform the school’s goals and ensure that the plan reflects what matters most to our community. Math teachers will utilize three programs to engage families on math work, including XtraMath, ALEKS, and Big Ideas Math. All three platforms can be used to monitor student understanding and progress over time. Additionally, XtraMath generates reports and certificates which can be sent automatically to parents and teachers depending on user preferences. During student-led conferences, which are bi-annual, students will self-select math work that they are proud of to show to their families. They will discuss why they are proud of the work, the circumstances that helped them be successful, and how they could have improved upon the work if applicable.

This instructional priority stems from SBA data (2024–2025), which revealed that it was a weaker section compared to others. The data further indicated that constructed-response and evidence- based reasoning questions related to literary passages were among the lowest-performing targets, particularly those assessing inference, theme development, and analysis of character and plot. Strengthening students’ ability to analyze and interpret literary texts is critical to ensuring overall reading proficiency and readiness for more complex literary analysis in upper grades. In addition, literary text comprehension supports broader literacy

content.strategies_summarized: Rose Hill Middle School will implement a comprehensive, data-driven approach to strengthen student foundations in 6th and 7th grade math through multiple coordinated initiatives. Math teachers will collaborate in data-focused Professional Learning Community meetings to develop targeted strategies for identified concept and procedure gaps, while simultaneously administering the FastBridge Universal Screener three times throughout the year to establish baseline data and monitor intervention effectiveness. Teachers will leverage ALEKS practice activities and Pride Time interventions to provide students with targeted support and skill-building opportunities, supplement these efforts with student listening sessions to understand their experiences and self-efficacy, and participate in grade-level team meetings to ensure consistent implementation and progress monitoring across all math classrooms.
content.currentdata: SBA: Last year, 80% of 6th graders (an increase of 8% from the previous year) and 78% of 7th graders (an increase of 10% from the previous year) scored a Level 3 (Met Standard) or Level 4 (Exceeded Standard) on the Math SBA. This is worthy of celebration and evidence that last year’s focus on providing students opportunities to retake assessments after reteaching/re- learning has taken place between attempts, so that they will continue learning after assessments, learn from their mistakes, and move closer to mastery, had a positive impact on student achievement. Last year on the SBA, 6th graders were Above the Proficiency Standard on all Concept and Procedures “Targets”. However, in the previous year, Target B was identified as a weakness, and Target I was the only one that was “At/Near Proficiency Standard”, so it is worthy of focusing on these specific areas. Last year on the SBA, 7th graders had two targets, Target F and Target G where they were “At/Near Proficiency Standard”, and another that Above Standard but still identified as an “Area of Weakness”: Target I.

content.outcome: To build community, encourage teamwork, reinforce the school values of Safe, Kind, and Responsible and promote school spirit, our school will implement a House system. Students and staff will be assigned to one of six houses, each representing core values and school pride. Continued implementation of restorative practices across the continuum (affective statements, affective questions, small impromptu conversations, circles, formal conferences), especially the 80% that are proactive, community-building focused, will lead to a greater sense of belonging for students.
content.focus_group: School-Wide Houses and Continued Implementation of Restorative Practices
content.strategies_summarized: Rose Hill Middle School will establish a House system where all students are randomly assigned to one of six houses with mixed grade levels, staying together for all three years, and will introduce this system during special First House Meetings within the first two weeks of school. To build engagement and school spirit, houses will earn points through academics, behavior, and extracurricular activities such as fundraisers, spirit days, and competitions, with the highest-scoring house winning the House Cup and increased participation expected across all school events. Additionally, ten staff members trained in International Institute of Restorative Practices will lead ongoing professional development during LEAP time, embedding proactive restorative practices like community circles into the Advisory curriculum, utilizing fair process for establishing norms, and engaging students in restorative circles to repair harm and restore relationships when conflicts arise.
content.currentdata: A sense of belonging impacts student performance, attendance, peer relationships, and school culture. Each student will be assigned to a House (six different houses named for different sub-species of lions, our school mascot), with an even distribution of 6th, 7th, and 8th grade students per house. Students will be engaged in developing a house chant, motto, crest, and decorating their pod as they work collaboratively to create their house’s individual identity. Student leaders, “House Captains,” will be chosen to help lead the work. Houses will compete and earn points through house competitions (academic, behavior, and extracurricular activities), events, and meetings. Restorative Practices foster a greater sense of belonging by creating a supportive and inclusive environment where students feel valued and heard. These practices, such as restorative circles, encourage open dialogue and mutual respect among students and teachers, helping build strong relationships and a positive school climate. This approach promotes a sense of safety and belonging, which is critical for students’ emotional and academic development. In the Panorama Spring survey, 53% of students gave positive responses to questions related to a sense of belonging (15% of students gave negative responses and 32% gave neutral responses). This showed an increase in positive response rate in this category of 9% and a decrease in negative responses by 4% compared to the year before. While this is evidence that the
content.engagement_strategies: The house structure, purpose of houses, and different house activities will be communicated to parents and families in the weekly newsletter that goes home to all RHMS families via ParentSquare. Parents will be reminded to encourage their students to wear their house colors on days there will be house meetings.

content.outcome: ML students will graduate at the same rate as our school’s overall graduation rate, with the goal of 100% of all students graduating.
content.focus_area: ML students have been graduating at a lower rate than our overall school’s graduation rate.
content.strategies_summarized: Eastlake High School will implement a comprehensive monitoring and support system for multilingual (ML) students at risk of not graduating. The school will send biweekly D/N lists to counselors, case managers, ML teachers, and administrators who will track at-risk ML students using detailed spreadsheets, gather direct feedback from students about their challenges and support needs, and communicate these insights through staff newsletters, Classrooms of the Week features, and targeted mid-quarter messages to teachers emphasizing the critical importance of intervention. Additionally, after the first semester, the school will encourage teachers to provide additional instructional support to help ML students improve failing grades and will facilitate schedule changes into Credit Recovery classes to ensure students remain on track to graduate.
content.currentdata: For the graduating class of 2024, 66.7% of ML students graduated on time, compared to our overall graduation rate of 97.68%. The graduating class of 2025 had only ten ML seniors: Five (50%) graduated on time, one (10%) did not, and four (40%) have IEPs and are continuing their high school education at our district’s Transition Academy.

content.focus_area: Tardies (T and L) and unexcused absences (U and W)
content.strategies_summarized: Eastlake High School will implement a comprehensive approach to reduce tardies and unexcused absences by assigning dedicated academic intervention teachers (0.6 FTE for unexcused absences and 0.4 FTE for tardies) to develop and implement targeted interventions at different threshold levels with escalating consequences. The school will also communicate the importance of regular, punctual attendance to students and families through messages in newsletters, while maintaining spreadsheets to track student progress across intervention levels. These coordinated efforts aim to decrease both the total number of tardies/lates and unexcused absences as well as reduce the number of students exceeding 20 instances in each category.
content.currentdata: Last year our students were Tardy or Late 11,892 times for their academic classes (does not include Wolf Time). This is an undercount; some teachers started recording their attendance several minutes into the class period because so many students were chronically late. Last year 130 students were marked T/L 20+ times. Last year 2194 students had at least one unexcused absence (U or W), and 711 students had at least 20.
content.engagement_strategies: Interventions for both tardies and for unexcused absences: - Level 1: Email sent to students and parents, informing them of the problem and why this is important. - Level 2: Meet with student, start learning about student, assign detention, inform parents.

content.strategies_summarized: Lake Washington High School will implement a comprehensive multi-pronged approach to ensure all freshmen earn at least six credits by the end of the year, beginning with early identification and support through counselor meetings in October, parent orientation in August, and transition meetings with middle school teams to identify focus students. The school will provide targeted engagement through the AVID program, Connections Lunch events with supplies support, and weekly attendance monitoring by the Attendance Specialist and counselors to address barriers to credit completion. Additionally, teachers will prioritize Tier I instructional strategies that provide multiple opportunities for students to demonstrate proficiency, while counselors will conduct quarterly reviews of the N List and hold one-on-one meetings with freshmen to build relationships and intervene early when students fall behind.

ILT will offer brief coaching to teachers around positive behavior interventions for 9th grade students, as well as coaching for PLCs. This support will be offered to teachers via the Behavior Support Form. Ninth Grade Parent Orientation was provided for parents of all 9th grade students in August. A transcript of the presentation was provided for those who could not attend in person. Parents met the administrative team and heard from leadership students about how students can get engaged. Small group choice sessions were offered on AP coursework, AVID and ML support, attendance and behavior support, technology access, clubs and sports. Families of students pre-identified as needing support for academics and attendance were invited to a Connections lunch before school started and also received a direct invitation to Curriculum Night. School supplies were provided for students and distributed by the Family Engagement specialist.

content.strategies_summarized: Lake Washington High School will achieve on-time graduation next year through a multi-faceted approach that combines proactive communication, targeted academic support, and leveraging teacher expertise. Counselors will maintain continuous contact with students and families via email and Parent Square messages, while simultaneously pushing into the RISE program on a bi-weekly basis to provide in-classroom support and facilitate summer school and HOP session sign-ups. Additionally, the school will identify juniors and seniors who have not met Washington State graduation requirements and assign them adult monitors for Canvas course completion, send at-risk letters every nine weeks to track progress, and utilize PLC-trained teachers to support content teams in improving student success outcomes while expanding peer mentoring programs to foster cross-grade relationships.

content.outcome: That graduation rate will consistently increase for all student groups, from 94.3% to 100% graduation rate in June 2026.
content.strategies_summarized: Redmond High School will implement a comprehensive, multi-faceted approach to increase graduation rates to 100% by June 2026, including expanding credit recovery options through Apex and summer school, offering dual credit and personalized pathway opportunities like Running Start and WANIC, and utilizing an MTSS Academic team to monitor student achievement through a Skyward watchlist. The school will strengthen instructional quality and cultural responsiveness through PLC collaboration with dedicated training and professional learning opportunities, while simultaneously supporting student engagement and family connection through multi-lingual family nights, an on-site Communities in Schools program that provides direct student support and resource navigation, and restorative discipline practices that reduce exclusionary suspensions. Additionally, the school will improve data tracking by confirming the placement of transfer students and coordinating closely among counselors, administrators, and support staff to identify and support at-risk students before they disengage.
content.engagement_strategies: • Dedicated staff meeting time for school/home communication. • Invite ML families to school meetings, and secure interpreters or native speakers for support. • Communicate with families about alternative pathways (WANIC, Running Start, etc) to ensure they are aware of options available for their student. • Present SIP and progress monitoring during PTSA Board meetings and General Membership meetings. • Connect with families during GT, IEP, and 504 meetings to continue building supportive relationships. • Curriculum Night – families visit RHS and travel their student’s schedule to meet teachers and learn about classes.

content.outcome: Increase the percentage of students who respond favorably to the overall Sense of Belonging questions in the Panorama Student Survey.
content.strategies_summarized: Redmond High School will implement a comprehensive approach to increase students' sense of belonging by fostering connections through structured homeroom activities, the Link Crew program for 9th grade transition, a unified classroom cell phone policy to enhance interpersonal engagement, and student recognition initiatives like the Mustang of the Month program. Additionally, the school will support extracurricular clubs and affinity groups such as Latinos Unidos, AWARE, Black Student Union, Fellowship of Christian Athletes, Indian Student Association, and SAGA to create inclusive spaces where students can connect around shared identities and interests. Finally, the school will conduct student focus groups to gather qualitative feedback on the school experience from diverse student populations, ensuring that all voices are heard and informing ongoing improvements to the school community.

When you are at school, how much do you feel like you belong? 50% Fall 2025: Sense of Belonging overall: 51% favorable Q4. When you are at school, how much do you feel like you belong? 56%

content.outcome: Increase the percentage of 9th students earning all credits from baseline of 91.14% in 2024-25 to 93% in 2025-26.
content.focus_area: Our focus group includes 9th grade students who either have not completed Algebra 1 or show academic evidence of need in the first quarter.
content.focus_group: 9th grade students will earn all six credits during their 9th grade year.
content.strategies_summarized: Nikola Tesla STEM High School will implement a comprehensive support system to increase the percentage of 9th grade students earning all credits from 91.14% to 93% by informing all teachers of students who have not yet completed Algebra 1 and developing individualized support plans, supported by monthly academic checks for students in the focus area. Additionally, administrators will analyze academic success data at each Skyward grade update period to identify students falling below target and ensure that every such student participates in a student of concern conference or receives Tier 2 support services.
content.currentdata: Data from previous years for students who start at Tesla STEM, but who have not successfully completed Algebra 1, show evidence of ongoing academic struggle. Academic data from 1st quarter grades, specifically grades below 70% (D+, D and N grades) will be reviewed and used to track ongoing achievement.
content.engagement_strategies: Tier 1: Administrators will communicate with all 9th grade families of the importance of successfully earning all credits and the specific impacts of the move from a 7-period to a 6-period day. Tier 2: Counselors will engage in family meetings at the quarter if a student is not independently showing a trajectory of successfully earning all credits, including establishing an expected schedule to attend teacher office hours.

strategies.action: Inform all teachers of which students have not yet completed Algebra 1 and make individual support plans for each student.
strategies.measures: Monthly academic checks for students in the focus area.

strategies.action: Administrators will analyze academic success data at each Skyward grade update period to identify any students who are falling below target.
strategies.measures: Ensure that every student who is falling below passing scores has been brought forward on a student of concern conference or receives a Tier 2 support.

content.outcome: Students who receive special education or 504 supports will graduate at the same rate as their peers.
content.focus_area: Increase 4-year graduation rates as appropriate for students receiving special education services or 504 support.
content.focus_group: Students who are receiving special education or 504 support.
content.strategies_summarized: Nikola Tesla STEM High School will implement a multi-tiered approach to ensure students with special education or 504 supports graduate at the same rate as their peers. The school will maintain a deliberate and persistent focus on earning all necessary graduation credits throughout all grades, monitored through semester grade reports, while simultaneously engaging with students and families through comprehensive IEP processes to ensure each plan fully supports individual student needs and remains compliant and complete. Additionally, for seniors at risk of not graduating, the school will develop individualized graduation plans that include adjusted schedules, access to mental health support, safety plans, and regular check-ins with documented meetings that connect families to school and district resources.
content.currentdata: The 2025 4-year graduation rate for all students was 97%. The number of students in the target group is suppressed for privacy. However, in 2025, there was a discrepancy between students with disabilities and students without on 4-year graduation rates.
content.engagement_strategies: Include graduation and credit discussion in IEP and 504 annual meetings to ensure that students and families are aware of credit status. Co-create and document the recovery plan.

strategies.action: Tier 3: Individualized plans to graduation for every senior who is in danger of not graduating, including adjusted schedules, access to mental health support, safety plans, and regular check-ins.
strategies.measures: Document regular meetings with students and families which include information about school and district resources for mental health support.

strategies.action: Engage with students and families through the IEP process to ensure the IEP fully supports the students’ needs.
strategies.measures: Ensure that every IEP is compliant and complete.

content.outcome: By the end of the 2025-26 school year, 11th grade students will earn a mean score of 4.3 or higher on the AP exam Synthesis Essay. This ELA skill supports STEM courses and is a requirement for achieving STEM literacy.
content.focus_area: Students in grades 9 – 11 will synthesize from multiple texts to improve their synthesis writing.
content.strategies_summarized: Nikola Tesla STEM High School will implement a comprehensive approach to synthesis instruction across all 11th grade ELA classes, with teachers ensuring alignment and consistency through common scoring protocols. Teachers will deliver explicit, intentional instruction on synthesis using exemplar essays, with teacher pairs working together to maintain fidelity while monitoring student growth throughout the year. Additionally, students will complete five practice essays during 11th grade, receiving teacher feedback and engaging in self-assessment through portfolio review to develop their synthesis skills and prepare for the AP exam.
content.currentdata: Student achievement on the AP Synthesis essay in 2025 was 4.24, representing a consistent participation of over 90% of 11th grade students participating in the AP Language and Composition exam.
content.engagement_strategies: Through the new learning management system, Canvas, families can see student progress and achievement, including teacher feedback on individual essays. Tier 2 strategy is to engage families directly when students are below the expected achievement, through teacher, counselor or administrator meetings.

strategies.action: Synthesis is taught several times in all ELA classes, building on skills from previous years.
strategies.measures: Teacher alignment with expectations and common scoring of the synthesis essays to ensure fidelity across teachers.

strategies.action: Teachers will deliver explicit teaching on synthesis using exemplar essays.
strategies.measures: Teacher pairs will intentionally and consistently deliver explicit teaching on synthesis; student achievement will show growth in their writing throughout the year.

strategies.action: Students will complete 5 practice essays in 11th grade.
strategies.measures: In addition to teacher feedback, students will self-assess their writing through the portfolio review.
